<h2>What Is Honey Processing?</h2>

<p>
  Honey processing (also called pulped natural) is a method where the outer skin (pulp) of the coffee cherry is removed mechanically, but the <strong>mucilage</strong> — the sticky, sugar-rich layer between pulp and parchment — is left on the seed (green bean) during drying. The name "honey" refers to the viscous, honey-like appearance of this mucilage, not to the use of actual honey or to a guaranteed honey flavor in the cup.
</p>

<p>
  Sitting between washed (fully washed) and natural (unwashed) processing, honey processing combines characteristics of both. Unlike washed processing, mucilage is not removed in fermentation tanks. Unlike natural processing, the cherry is not dried whole with the fruit still attached. This middle path creates a distinctive flavor profile that has grown increasingly popular in specialty coffee.
</p>

<h3>Understanding Mucilage</h3>
<p>
  A coffee cherry's structure, from outside in: outer skin (pulp) → mucilage layer → parchment (endocarp) → silver skin → green bean. Mucilage is a thick, pectin-rich layer high in sugars and organic acids. During drying, compounds from the mucilage are believed to migrate into the seed — influencing the sugars, acids, and body-contributing compounds in the final cup. The quantity of mucilage left on the bean during drying is the primary variable that defines honey processing.
</p>

<h2>Classification by Mucilage Remaining</h2>

<p>
  Honey processing is categorized by the percentage of mucilage remaining after pulping. While industry definitions vary across regions, roasters, and buyers, the color classification system popularized in Costa Rica is the most widely used framework.
</p>

