<h2>Processing Steps</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Step</th>
      <th>Description</th>
      <th>Purpose</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>1. Harvest and sort</strong></td>
      <td>Selectively pick ripe cherries. Float in water to remove defects and underripe cherries</td>
      <td>Ensure input quality and uniformity</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>2. Pulping</strong></td>
      <td>Run cherries through a depulper (pulping machine) to remove the outer skin</td>
      <td>Expose the mucilage-covered seed</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>3. Mucilage adjustment</strong></td>
      <td>Control how much mucilage remains using depulper settings, rotating discs, or screens</td>
      <td>Hit the target honey "color" classification</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>4. African bed drying</strong></td>
      <td>Spread in thin layers on raised drying beds. Turn regularly for even airflow</td>
      <td>Even drying, mold prevention</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>5. Monitoring</strong></td>
      <td>Dry until moisture content reaches 11–12%. Black honey requires weeks of careful management</td>
      <td>Prevent over-drying (cracking) or over-fermentation (off-flavors)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>6. Hulling and grading</strong></td>
      <td>Remove parchment; sort by screen size and density; hand-pick visible defects</td>
      <td>Final quality control for export-grade green coffee</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Flavor Characteristics</h2>

<p>
  Honey processing produces a flavor profile that is genuinely distinct — not merely "between washed and natural" but possessing its own identity:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Sweetness:</strong> More pronounced than washed, less intense than natural. The mucilage's sugars appear to contribute to the perception of sweetness in the cup</li>
  <li><strong>Body:</strong> Fuller than washed, lighter than natural. Often described as creamy or silky — a characteristic texture</li>
  <li><strong>Acidity:</strong> Present but less sharp than washed. Often fruit-forward rather than bright-citrus, with a soft quality</li>
  <li><strong>Cleanliness:</strong> Dramatically cleaner than natural processing. Fermented or "wild" off-notes are largely absent with proper management</li>
  <li><strong>Complexity:</strong> Increases with mucilage level — Black Honey can approach natural's tropical fruit complexity without natural's fermented character</li>
</ul>

<h2>Origins and Adoption</h2>

<p>
  Honey processing was pioneered and systematized in <strong>Costa Rica</strong>. In the late 1990s and 2000s, strengthening environmental regulations made the water-intensive washed process problematic — processing mills were required to dramatically reduce water usage and manage pulp wastewater more carefully. Honey processing offered an elegant solution: it uses minimal water compared to washed, generates less wastewater, and produces excellent cup quality.
</p>

<p>
  Costa Rican processing mills developed and refined the color-based classification system, and their marketing of "Yellow Honey," "Red Honey," and "Black Honey" as distinct products helped introduce these concepts to the global specialty coffee trade. Today, honey processing has spread to El Salvador, Panama, Colombia, and beyond — where producers combine it with local varieties and terroir to create unique regional expressions.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Why Choose Honey Processed Coffee?</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>For buyers and roasters:</strong> The ideal choice when you want the clarity of washed with the body and sweetness of natural — particularly with beans that express themselves well with a slightly richer profile<br />
    <strong>For producers:</strong> More water-efficient than washed; lower fermentation risk than natural; fermentation tanks not required, reducing infrastructure cost<br />
    <strong>Environmental angle:</strong> In Costa Rica especially, honey processing represents a meaningful environmental improvement over traditional fully-washed processing<br /><br />
    When tasting honey processed coffees, try a medium-light to medium roast to best showcase the sweetness and fruit complexity. Brewing side-by-side with a washed version of the same variety is one of the most illuminating experiments in coffee education.
  </p>
</div>

